>sometimes
Apostrophe is a special kind of thing.
- It has no sound values.
- It is not regarded as part of the alphabet.
- But its absence is enough for a word to be spelled incorrectly or to be misunderstood.
- And its presence does not imply a particular word.

Its role in contractions is a meta-character. You can always not use the contraction form so there it has no value in the message, only in how the message is encoded in text.

Its role in indicating possessive form is as a disambiguation tool, since the ending-s sound became indicative of both plural and possession and in text without indication of inflection the ambiguity is unwelcome. But then that is reversed when it's used as a connecting spacer (like a hyphen but without hyphenation's meanings being implied) to make numbers and abbreviations able to take the plural s, like "it was like that in the 70's" or "I've been living off of ramen and MRE's."

Which is even more fun because "the 70's" is used for plural, while "Back in '76" is used for a specific year with that apostrophe being indicative of omission. But "The '70's" doesn't work well because then it's too easily confused with single quotes. And don't get me started on the nightmare of when Microsoft Word starts "helping" by replacing apostrophe with opening or closing single quote to make it "look nicer" causing leading apostrophe of omission to be single opening quote, like "back in ‘76" which is very wrong, or fucks up "HawaiÊ»i" which should at least be "Hawai‘i" but Microsoft so it makes "Hawai’i" because their implementation seems to be ‘ if it has whites pace before it and ’ if it has a printing character before it.

And all that because we all were happy with the vertical mark compromises, ' and ", when we didn't have the resources for better, but once we did, Unicode on one side and Microsoft on the other made it a fucking mess.

Fun fact: in Polish grammar, you only ever use apostrophes when you write foreign names in a Polish sentence where they end on a letter that's not pronounced.

So for example, if you want to write "Tom Hanks'" in Polish, you'll write "Toma Hanksa" as you pronounce both the "a" and the "s", but in case of "George Clooney's" you'll write "George'a Clooneya", since you don't make the "e" sound while pronouncing "George", so you need that apostrophe to make it clear you pronounce it differently than it is written.

Additionally, the name "Charles" will have an apostrophe or not depending on whether or not it's English or French. In English, you pronounce the "s", but in French the "s" is silent. So in case of English, "Charles'" would be "Charlesa" but in French it would be "Charles'a".

It's a grammatical rule that a lot of Polish people have issue with and people with degrees keep fucking it up, adding an apostrophe where there shouldn't be one and not adding it where there should be one. But it's only ever used with foreign names, otherwise it's absent outside of cases like year shorthands (1993 as '93), since with abbreviations you use a hyphen (you write "DJ's" as "DJ-a" and not "DJ'a").

Polish is one of the few languages where for the most part you read words as they are written outside of very, very few cases, so made up tongue twisters like "Grzegorz BrzÄczyszczykiewicz, ChrzÄszczyÅ¼ewoszyce powiat ÅÄkoÅody" and "KonstantynopolitaÅczykowianeczka" are ironically trivial to pronounce, every letter and digraph is pronounced as it is written with no oddities like the "fish/ghoti" of English.
